# Browserslist Example Configuration
# Copy this file to your project root as .browserslistrc
# and uncomment the target that fits your needs.
#
# For more on Baseline targets:
#   https://web.dev/articles/use-baseline-with-browserslist
#   https://web-platform-dx.github.io/web-features/
#
# If no .browserslistrc or browserslist config exists in the project,
# the web-compat-audit skill falls back to: > 0.5%, last 2 versions, not dead

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPTION 1: Baseline Newly Available
#
# Features that are interoperable across Chrome, Edge, Firefox, and Safari
# but became so within the last 30 months. This is the "leading edge" of
# safe cross-browser support — you get modern APIs, but you accept that
# users on browsers older than ~2.5 years may not be covered.
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------

# baseline newly available

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPTION 2: Baseline Newly Available + downstream browsers
#
# Same as above, but also includes Chromium-based browsers beyond Chrome
# and Edge (Opera, Samsung Internet, Brave, Arc, etc.) and WebKit-based
# browsers on iOS beyond Safari.
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------

# baseline newly available with downstream

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPTION 3: Baseline Widely Available
#
# Features that have been interoperable for 30 months or more.
# The conservative choice — broad compatibility, but you miss out on
# newer APIs that haven't yet graduated to Widely Available.
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------

# baseline widely available

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPTION 4: Baseline year (pin to a specific feature set)
#
# Includes all features that were Newly Available at the end of the
# specified year. Useful for reproducible builds and for teams that
# want to adopt a fixed baseline and upgrade deliberately.
#
# Examples:
#   baseline 2023  →  Chrome 120, Edge 120, Firefox 121, Safari 17.2
#   baseline 2024  →  whatever was interoperable by end of 2024
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------

# baseline 2024

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPTION 5: Traditional browserslist query (non-Baseline)
#
# The classic approach using market share and version counts.
# Still a valid choice, especially if you need to support specific
# browsers or versions not covered by the Baseline model.
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------

# > 0.5%, last 2 versions, not dead
